               <note>Fiey provides the following bibliographic citations: <quote source="#bibl1234-1">Cf. DHGE, XV, col. 1473-75 (M. Spanneut). BS, V, 261- 62 (R. Janin) .</quote>
               </note>
               <note type="abstract">The Syriac life was translated and commented on by Devos.  In this version, Eusebius is already bishop of Samosata when he receives a visit from Jacob of Nisibis, who allows him to build a big church.   He ordains priests and bishops during the Arian controversy and was a good friend of the Cappadocians.  He is killed by a blow to the head by an Arian woman.   </note>
